# PDB Parallel Data Pipeline

A parallelized protein structure ingestion and preprocessing pipeline built
with Dask and BioPython. Downloads PDB files from RCSB, extracts per-residue
features, and writes a clean Parquet-ready dataset — demonstrating HPC-style
parallel data engineering on real scientific data.

Built as part of an NSF ACCESS allocation preparation portfolio.

---

## Pipeline Architecture
```
PDB IDs (text file)
      │
  Dask Bag (lazy sequence of IDs)
      │
  map: download .pdb via RCSB REST API
      │
  map: parse with BioPython → per-residue features
       (residue type, chain ID, B-factor, coords x/y/z)
      │
  filter: skip failed downloads and malformed structures
      │
  flatten → Dask DataFrame
      │
  write to CSV / Parquet
```

---

## Benchmark Results

Tested on 100, 250, and 500 PDB structures with 4 parallel workers vs serial.

| Structures | Serial (s) | Dask 4-workers (s) | Speedup |
|------------|------------|---------------------|---------|
| 100        | 97.61      | 7.74                | 12.61x  |
| 250        | 134.57     | 19.23               | 7.00x   |
| 500        | 233.17     | 37.31               | 6.25x   |

![Benchmark Plot](output/benchmark_speedup.png)

### Why does speedup decrease from 12x to 6x?

At n=100 all downloads are fresh — pure network I/O where threads overlap
waiting time almost perfectly, exceeding the theoretical 4x ceiling.
At n=250 and n=500 a growing fraction of structures are already cached on
disk, so the bottleneck shifts from network I/O to local parsing. Parsing
is CPU-bound, where thread-based parallelism is limited by Python's GIL.
This is a real HPC phenomenon: the optimal parallelism strategy depends on
whether your bottleneck is I/O-bound or CPU-bound.

---

## Features

- Lazy parallel execution via Dask Bag
- Fault-tolerant: malformed files and 404s are logged and skipped
- Caching: already-downloaded structures are never re-fetched
- Structured logging with loguru
- Outputs a clean CSV with residue-level features ready for ML ingestion

---

## Extracted Features

| Column     | Description                              |
|------------|------------------------------------------|
| `pdb_id`   | RCSB structure identifier                |
| `chain`    | Chain ID within the structure            |
| `res_name` | Three-letter residue name (e.g. ALA)     |
| `res_seq`  | Residue sequence number                  |
| `ca_x/y/z` | Alpha-carbon 3D coordinates (Angstroms)  |
| `b_factor` | Crystallographic B-factor (flexibility)  |

---

## Setup
```bash
python -m venv venv
venv\Scripts\activate        # Windows
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

---

## Usage
```bash
cd src

# Run the Dask pipeline on 10 default structures
python pipeline.py

# Run the full benchmark across 100/250/500 structures
python benchmark.py
```

---

## Project Structure
```
pdb_pipeline/
├── src/
│   ├── fetch.py          # RCSB downloader with error handling
│   ├── parser.py         # BioPython PDB parser
│   ├── pipeline.py       # Serial + Dask runners
│   ├── benchmark.py      # Speedup benchmark and plots
│   └── pdb_ids.txt       # 500 curated PDB IDs
├── output/
│   ├── benchmark_speedup.png
│   └── benchmark_results.csv
└── README.md
```

